Getting anxiety meds and ADHD meds on top of antidepressants finally made me realise the exact difference between the three types of executive dysfunction.
So grateful for the pills!! 💊💊💊

Anxiety makes me avoid things, also sit still & bite my nails incessantly, while sorta reading/watching sth but not really.
ADHD paralysis might also look like sitting w/out moving, but often it's  moving around constantly, but not being able to get started on *the* task.

This was the EXACT wording I was googling when I first realised antidepressnts weren't enough to make me *do* things.
But depression is like slowly wading through thick water - I've only ever experienced this "inability to move" w/ ADHD & w/ anxiety (but they are a bit different) https://t.co/mBNS2SW87N

@dykegardens @Lisa86550169 @FlockingCrazy @JonesSeeker @annagranta Meds are honestly the only thing I think for sure helps me... unfortunately lots of tips for other ADHD things out there that are great, but for me, meds are the only thing that stops the paralysis 😕
So yeah, ADHD is a bitch, but I love that bitch sometimes 😅

And honestly I think this whole experience, my mental health & neurodivergence journey made me a better, more empathetic & more functional person.
Before I might have blamed myself or others for certain behaviours, but now I can tell when someone needs help.

I still feel like I'm not "right in the head" occasionally, but now I know that it's common in ND ppl & I can shut those thoughts down.
Being on multiple medications and having been in the psych ward, I learnt to recognise when it was ADHD, anxiety, depression vs *true* laziness.

I'd probably still live w/out knowing I wasn't just lazy, broken and stupid. I am so grateful for the youtube algorithm and everyone in my life who *didn't* say "we're all a little ADHD sometimes", bc there were also those people and they made me doubt myself even more 😕

But I swear, if it weren't for that random YouTube recommendation, and for my girlfriend confirming my doubts, and for my students, and for an acquaintance who told me where I can get evaluated, and for the hundreds of women w/ ADHD on FB who had similar experiences.... 🥺

that my evaluation would be negative - I wouldn't have ADHD. I got it and I DID have it. Then I was sure I'd never get any meds for it. And yet I did get them, and they did change everything.
In hindsight I can't believe I doubted myself so much when I was so sure of my students!

So all the while knowing abt ADHD and even using strategies on myself and on my students and it working - STILL I doubted myself. "I can't have it really, I must be lazy."
I wanted to get evaluated but was sure I'd never get the appointment. I went and got it. Then I was sure tht

My change in approach while teaching her was midly effective in the classroom and it did improve her achievement a bit, but I think it must have done wonders for her self-esteem! At least I can hope it did bc I have zero idea where she is now as I don't teach anymore.

I started to treat her differently bc I judged her inability to comply w/ class rules to be bc of ADHD.
It must have worked bc one day I was welcomed by her grandma who picked her up, and she gifted me a jar of homemade bitter orange jam bc I was "Nelly's favourite teacher" 😳

I had a particularly sweet interaction w/ one of them that will forever remain one of my dearest memories in teaching. I doubt I could ever forget Nelly 💖
She was a bit "naughty" & her classmates treated her as such, I think bc her homeroom teacher did as well and was strict.

I joined Facebook groups for adults and women w/ ADHD and found myself more and more sure it was truly the one thing that explained my poor functioning despite being treated for depression.
I started recognising ADHD in some of my students, especially girls, even the "good" ones.

So I said to my ex "maybe I don't have only depression like you, maybe I am ADHD too" and we both googled signs & symptoms like crazy and both of came to the conclusion that I very much indeed had ADHD. She even pointed out things to me I wasn't aware I was doing, that were ADHD.

YT must have recommended it bc at the time I worked as a teacher, and that involves ADHD students. But I found myself thinking "wait a minute, ALL of these suggestions for helping them sound like the EXACT thing that would help me!" (I'm very introspective & self-aware) "wtf? 🤨"

I'd been in treatment for depression for a while and living with my ex gf who also had depression. Antidepressants helped w/ my mood but not my functionality, like they did for her. We were both baffled by it until I stumbled upon this video:

I realised in group therapy I wasn't just grieving the loss of a relationship, I was (I am) grieving the loss of a life that I had.
My gf wasn't just a lover, she was a life partner, a business partner, a DM for our DnD group, a bird parent to our cockatiels.

I learnt love comes in many forms, and that I *AM* loved, by so many people, and by myself as well.
I learnt everything might dissappear in the blink of an eye (not just bc of the breakup, but also bc a friend died of cancer at 29), and I should cherish every moment, every text.

I learnt life can change overnight; a seemingly tight-knit &strong friend group dissolves when ppl r forced to take sides.
I learnt I was wrong thinking #DnD inevitably creates friends4lyf, but also tht some ppl u thought were just acquaintances show up when u need help the most.

I learnt about my shadow self: my bad sides (manipulative, needy, aggressive, selfish, arrogant, moody), my suppressed sides (humour, joy, daringness), my wounds (abandonment, rejection, betrayal), my self-sabotage (procrastination, no self care & responsibility, avoiding) etc.🖤

I learnt that no amount of common life goals and personality compatibility guarantees that sort of life materialising. We might *want* the same things, but maybe we just can't achieve them together in this moment in our lives.
Maybe my life goals are my own to accomplish.

I learnt that you can still love someone so so much, and yet let them go. And sometimes, that's the most loving thing you can do for them in that moment. 💖🙏🏼😟
And maybe, just maybe, the love you shared wasn't in vain. It was so precious, & in the end, "we'll always have Paris".

I learnt that, even tho she may be the ❤ of my life, and I will ALWAYS love her, unconditionally - WANTING someone who DOESN'T want YOU is not worth it! It's not worth the pain, the suffering, the begging, the pushing, the wanting to mould yourself into what u think they want.

Learning how, just because you move in together, doesn't mean you should have done it; just bc you live together doesn't mean that's good for *both* of you; just bc they wanna move in doesn't mean they're ready to commit.
And finally, living alone is harder than together w/ some1
